<ns5671:section xmlns:ns5671="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.platforms.linux.shell.scripting.iteration.until">

  <ns5672:title xmlns:ns5672="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Repeat-until loops</ns5672:title>
  <ns5673:para xmlns:ns5673="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    The third iterative construct used in shell scripts is the 
    <ns5674:emphasis xmlns:ns5674="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">repeat</ns5674:emphasis>-<ns5675:command xmlns:ns5675="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">until</ns5675:command> loop. The difference
    between the <ns5676:command xmlns:ns5676="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">while</ns5676:command> and the
    <ns5677:emphasis xmlns:ns5677="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">repeat</ns5677:emphasis>-<ns5678:command xmlns:ns5678="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">until</ns5678:command> loop is that
    the former executes the iterative block at least once, even if the test condition
    never holds <ns5679:emphasis xmlns:ns5679="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">true</ns5679:emphasis> (1), while the <ns5680:command xmlns:ns5680="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">while</ns5680:command>
    loop performs the test before the iterative block.
  </ns5673:para>
  <ns5681:para xmlns:ns5681="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    The command is illustrated with the following script:
    <ns5682:programlisting xmlns:ns5682="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
<xi:include xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" href="source/guess_sh.docbook"/>      
    </ns5682:programlisting>
    Running the script may yield the following output:
    <ns5683:programlisting xmlns:ns5683="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
Guess my secret number (between 0 and 9)
3
Guess my secret number (between 0 and 9)
0
Guess my secret number (between 0 and 9)
9
Guess my secret number (between 0 and 9)
7
Congratulations!! You finally guessed it.
    </ns5683:programlisting>
  </ns5681:para>
</ns5671:section>